description.narrative:
General question: Results related to the intended outcome 2016Question: Summarise results related to the intended outcome (this information will be sent to Open Aid)Answer: The goal of the SHARED project was ‘to contribute to the reduction of rural poverty through improved service delivery by Farm Business Advisors (FBAs)’. We aim to do this by lifting 20,000 smallholder farmers out of poverty using market-led approaches to support subsistence level smallholders make the shift to more lucrative agricultural sub sectors and value chains that offer growing income opportunities. Core to our approach is supporting FBAs to become micro entrepreneurs, who support their own network of client farmers in accessing inputs, advice, credit and markets. The following is the summary of the results that were obtained in the last two years of the shared project; iDE
• exceeded the target for average change in net farm income by 154%, realizing a net change of US$201.72 per participating household;
•exceeded target for number of farm enterprises reached through FBAs by 118% as some 23,613 farm enterprises benefited from FBA support;
•200 FBAs are actively transacting and earning, 100% of our target;  
•FBAs earned some ZMW 2.4million in commissions or margins, 75% of the target for FBA earnings; 
•iDE piloted a stock guarantee scheme with a good cross section of input suppliers to unlock timely access to inputs via FBAs;
•iDE successfully piloted FBA aggregation services for maize, soy and cowpeas with three lead buyers/traders (Amatheon Agri Zambia, World Food Programme and Export Trading Group);
•iDE completed  performance testing of the Sunflower solar pump (which was piggybacked on ‘SHARED’ and are poised to support the development of commercial distribution channels;
•136 FBAs were trained in safe handling and use of pesticides (68% of target).
Unfortunately, during this reporting period, gender aspects were not fully mainstreamed in the project. Therefore, the impact of the project on women participation the activities that iDE is promoting is under reported. However, the are numbers of women participating in some of the activities. 
